## How I Approach Building AI Agents and AI Practices

I treat AI agent development as an organizational design problem first, and a tooling exercise second. My approach focuses on building systems that can survive real operating environments, not just demos.

- Start with the current-state environment: where data lives, how it’s structured or unstructured, and which systems teams already use.
- Map how work actually flows across teams and tools before introducing any AI.
- Define the business problem and feasible use cases first, not the model.
- Bring governance, risk, and compliance requirements in at the beginning, not after building.
- Structure knowledge and taxonomies offline so AI behavior is reliable and reproducible.
- Design agent instructions, prompt logic, and evaluation criteria outside the tool to avoid trial-and-error building.
- Build and test iteratively using traces to identify failure modes.
- Add human-in-the-loop controls where judgment and accountability are required.
- Document lessons learned and define scaling requirements across cost, people, and governance.

The goal is simple: build AI systems that fit how organizations actually work, not how demos pretend they work.

